# Auto-commit to GitHub

After completing any code/file change in this project, automatically stage,
commit, and push to GitHub without waiting for the user to ask.

## Workflow
- Stage the changed files, commit with a clear message, then `git push origin HEAD:main`.
- Group a logical unit of work into one commit (don't commit half-finished states).
- Run this after the change builds/lints cleanly when a build/lint step is relevant.

## PowerShell notes (this is a Windows/pwsh environment)
- Do NOT use `&&` to chain commands; run them separately or with `;`.
- Do NOT use bash heredocs (`$(cat <<'EOF')`). Use multiple `-m` flags:

```powershell
git add <paths>
git commit -m "Short summary" -m "Optional body explaining why"
git push origin HEAD:main
```

## Safety
- Never commit secrets. `.env.local` is gitignored — keep it that way.
- Never `git push --force` to main, never change git config, never skip hooks.
- If a commit/push fails, surface the error instead of retrying destructively.
